VSo, people want a lot of things out of life,
p4
aVbut I think, more than anything else, they want happiness.
p5
aVAristotle called happiness "the chief good," the end
p6
aVtowards which all other things aim.
p7
aVAccording to this view, the reason we want a big house
p8
aVor a nice car
p9
aVor a good job
p10
aVisn't that these things are intrinsically valuable.
p11
aVIt's that we expect them to bring us
p12
aVhappiness.
p13
aa(lp14
VNow in the last 50 years, we Americans have gotten
p15
aVa lot of the things that we want. We're richer.
p16
aVWe live longer. We have access to technology
p17
aVthat would have seemed like science fiction
p18
aVjust a few years ago.
p19
aVThe paradox of happiness is that even though the
p20
aVobjective conditions of our lives have improved dramatically,
p21
aVwe haven't actually gotten any happier.
p22
aa(lp23
VMaybe because these conventional notions of progress
p24
aVhaven't delivered big benefits in terms of happiness,
p25
aVthere's been an increased interest in recent years
p26
aVin happiness itself.
p27
aVPeople have been debating the causes of happiness
p28
aVfor a really long time, in fact for thousands of years,
p29
aVbut it seems like many of those debates remain unresolved.
p30
aVWell, as with many other domains in life, I think
p31
aVthe scientific method has the potential to answer this question.
p32
aVIn fact, in the last few years, there's been an explosion
p33
aVin research on happiness. For example, we've learned a lot
p34
aVabout its demographics, how things like income
p35
aVand education, gender and marriage relate to it.
p36
aVBut one of the puzzles this has revealed is that
p37
aVfactors like these don't seem to have a particularly strong effect.
p38
aVYes, it's better to make more money rather than less,
p39
aVor to graduate from college instead of dropping out,
p40
aVbut the differences in happiness tend to be small.
p41
aa(lp42
VWhich leaves the question, what are the big causes of happiness?
p43
aVI think that's a question we haven't really answered yet,
p44
aVbut I think something that has the potential to be an answer
p45
aVis that maybe happiness has an awful lot to do with
p46
aVthe contents of our moment-to-moment experiences.
p47
aVIt certainly seems that we're going about our lives,
p48
aVthat what we're doing, who we're with, what we're thinking about,
p49
aVhave a big influence on our happiness, and yet
p50
aVthese are the very factors that have been very difficult,
p51
aVin fact almost impossible, for scientists to study.
p52
aa(lp53
VA few years ago, I came up with a way to study people's happiness
p54
aVmoment to moment as they're going about their daily lives
p55
aVon a massive scale all over the world, something we'd never
p56
aVbeen able to do before. Called trackyourhappiness.org,
p57
aVit uses the iPhone to monitor people's happiness in real time.
p58
aVHow does this work? Basically, I send people signals
p59
aVat random points throughout the day, and then I ask them
p60
aVa bunch of questions about their moment-to-moment experience
p61
aVat the instant just before the signal.
p62
aVThe idea is that, if we can watch how people's happiness
p63
aVgoes up and down over the course of the day,
p64
aVminute to minute in some cases,
p65
aVand try to understand how what people are doing,
p66
aVwho they're with, what they're thinking about, and all
p67
aVthe other factors that describe our day, how those might
p68
aVrelate to those changes in happiness, we might be able
p69
aVto discover some of the things that really have
p70
aVa big influence on happiness.
p71
aVWe've been fortunate with this project to collect
p72
aVquite a lot of data, a lot more data of this kind than I think
p73
aVhas ever been collected before,
p74
aVover 650,000 real-time reports
p75
aVfrom over 15,000 people.
p76
aVAnd it's not just a lot of people, it's a really diverse group,
p77
aVpeople from a wide range of ages, from 18 to late 80s,
p78
aVa wide range of incomes, education levels,
p79
aVpeople who are married, divorced, widowed, etc.
p80
aVThey collectively represent every one of
p81
aV86 occupational categories and hail from over 80 countries.
