aa(lp83
VWhat I'd like to do with the rest of my time with you today
p84
aVis talk a little bit about one of the areas that we've been
p85
aVinvestigating, and that's mind-wandering.
p86
aVAs human beings, we have this unique ability
p87
aVto have our minds stray away from the present.
p88
aVThis guy is sitting here working on his computer,
p89
aVand yet he could be thinking about
p90
aVthe vacation he had last month,
p91
aVwondering what he's going to have for dinner.
p92
aVMaybe he's worried that he's going bald. (Laughter)
p93
aVThis ability to focus our attention on something other
p94
aVthan the present is really amazing. It allows us to learn
p95
aVand plan and reason in ways that no other species of animal can.
p96
aVAnd yet it's not clear what the relationship is
p97
aVbetween our use of this ability and our happiness.
p98
aVYou've probably heard people suggest that you should
p99
aVstay focused on the present. "Be here now,"
p100
aVyou've probably heard a hundred times.
p101
aVMaybe, to really be happy, we need to stay completely
p102
aVimmersed and focused on our experience in the moment.
p103
aVMaybe these people are right. Maybe mind-wandering
p104
aVis a bad thing.
p105
aVOn the other hand, when our minds wander,
p106
aVthey're unconstrained. We can't change the physical reality
p107
aVin front of us, but we can go anywhere in our minds.
p108
aVSince we know people want to be happy, maybe
p109
aVwhen our minds wander, they're going to someplace happier than the place
p110
aVthat they're leaving. It would make a lot of sense.
p111
aVIn other words, maybe the pleasures of the mind
p112
aVallow us to increase our happiness with mind-wandering.
p113
aa(lp114
VWell, since I'm a scientist, I'd like to try to
p115
aVresolve this debate with some data, and in particular
p116
aVI'd like to present some data to you from three questions
p117
aVthat I ask with Track Your Happiness. Remember, this is from
p118
aVsort of moment-to-moment experience in people's real lives.
p119
aVThere are three questions. The first one is a happiness question:
p120
aVHow do you feel, on a scale ranging from very bad
p121
aVto very good? Second, an activity question:
p122
aVWhat are you doing, on a list of 22 different activities
p123
aVincluding things like eating and working and watching TV?
p124
aVAnd finally a mind-wandering question:
p125
aVAre you thinking about something other
p126
aVthan what you're currently doing?
p127
aVPeople could say no \u2014 in other words, I'm focused only on my task \u2014
p128
aVor yes \u2014 I am thinking about something else \u2014
p129
aVand the topic of those thoughts are pleasant,
p130
aVneutral or unpleasant.
p131
aVAny of those yes responses are what we called mind-wandering.
p132
aa(lp133
VSo what did we find?
p134
aVThis graph shows happiness on the vertical axis,
p135
aVand you can see that bar there representing how happy
p136
aVpeople are when they're focused on the present,
p137
aVwhen they're not mind-wandering.
p138
aVAs it turns out, people are substantially less happy
p139
aVwhen their minds are wandering than when they're not.
p140
aVNow you might look at this result and say, okay, sure,
p141
aVon average people are less happy when they're mind-wandering,
p142
aVbut surely when their minds are straying away
p143
aVfrom something that wasn't very enjoyable to begin with,
p144
aVat least then mind-wandering should be doing something good for us.
p145
aVNope. As it turns out,
p146
aVpeople are less happy when they're mind-wandering
p147
aVno matter what they're doing. For example,
p148
aVpeople don't really like commuting to work very much.
p149
aVIt's one of their least enjoyable activities, and yet
p150
aVthey are substantially happier when they're focused
p151
aVonly on their commute than when their mind is going
p152
aVoff to something else.
p153
aVIt's amazing.
p154
aa(lp155
VSo how could this be happening? I think part of the reason,
p156
aVa big part of the reason, is that when our minds wander,
p157
aVwe often think about unpleasant things, and they are
p158
aVenormously less happy when they do that,
p159
aVour worries, our anxieties, our regrets,
p160
aVand yet even when people are thinking about something
p161
aVneutral, they're still considerably less happy
p162
aVthan when they're not mind-wandering at all.
p163
aVEven when they're thinking about something they would describe as pleasant,
p164
aVthey're actually just slightly less happy
p165
aVthan when they aren't mind-wandering.
p166
aVIf mind-wandering were a slot machine, it would be like
p167
aVhaving the chance to lose 50 dollars, 20 dollars
p168
aVor one dollar. Right? You'd never want to play. (Laughter)
p169
aa(lp170
VSo I've been talking about this, suggesting, perhaps,
p171
aVthat mind-wandering causes unhappiness, but all
p172
aVI've really shown you is that these two things are correlated.
p173
aVIt's possible that's the case, but it might also be the case
p174
aVthat when people are unhappy, then they mind-wander.
p175
aVMaybe that's what's really going on. How could we ever
p176
aVdisentangle these two possibilites?
p177
aVWell, one fact that we can take advantage of, I think a fact
p178
aVyou'll all agree is true, is that time goes forward, not
p179
aVbackward. Right? The cause has to come before the effect.
p180
aVWe're lucky in this data we have many responses from each person,
p181
aVand so we can look and see, does mind-wandering
p182
aVtend to precede unhappiness, or does unhappiness
p183
aVtend to precede mind-wandering, to get some insight
p184
aVinto the causal direction.
p185
aVAs it turns out, there is a strong relationship between
p186
aVmind-wandering now and being unhappy a short time later,
p187
aVconsistent with the idea that mind-wandering is causing people to be unhappy.
p188
aVIn contrast, there's no relationship between being unhappy
p189
aVnow and mind-wandering a short time later.
p190
aVIn other words, mind-wandering very likely seems to be
p191
aVan actual cause, and not merely a consequence, of unhappiness.
